{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"debb347d-8666-49d7-8d3c-f3df1474145d","content":"Here's how to collect a CPU trace from a .NET 8 app in a Windows container on K8s:\n\n### 1. Exec into the container\n```bash\nkubectl exec -it <pod-name> -- powershell\n```\n\n### 2. Install `dotnet-trace` (if not already present)\n```powershell\ndotnet tool install --global dotnet-trace\n```\n\n### 3. Find the process ID\n```powershell\ndotnet-trace ps\n```\n\n### 4. Collect the trace\n```powershell\ndotnet-trace collect -p <PID> --profile cpu-sampling --duration 00:00:30\n```\n\nThis writes a `.nettrace` file you can analyze in **Visual Studio** or **PerfView**.\n\n### Getting the file off the pod\n```bash\nkubectl cp <pod-name>:<path-to-trace-file> ./trace.nettrace\n```\n\n### Alternative: `dotnet-counters` for a quick look first\n```powershell\ndotnet tool install --global dotnet-counters\ndotnet-counters monitor -p <PID> --counters System.Runtime\n```\nThis gives real-time CPU %, GC, threadpool stats — useful before committing to a full trace.\n\n> **Tip:** If `dotnet tool install` fails (no SDK in the container), you can download the standalone `dotnet-trace` global tool from NuGet and copy it in via `kubectl cp`.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"d8b4670f-d589-49b1-a00b-b82f323cf87b","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking for guidance on collecting a performance trace for a .NET 8 application running in a Windows container on Kubernetes, where they're experiencing high CPU. This is a diagnostic/troubleshooting question, not a code change request. I'll provide concise guidance.","outputTokens":417,"requestId":"6003:3E203F:253C68:2C4B25:69EAC51A"},"id":"343c4480-1710-4975-8418-b7799a9a08f3","timestamp":"2026-04-24T01:19:31.408Z","parentId":"41b095dc-995e-4d2b-aec2-873131933042"}
